Heart Disease Prediction using Logistic Regression

Using anonymized publicaly available dataset by Cleveland Clinic Foundation on various patient characteristics and whether they have a heart disease, let's build a model using logistic regression to predict heart disease.

Puneet Pawar Wed 07 January 2026 Wed 07 January 2026
machine_learning sklearn regression classification imputation feature_importance interpreting_coefficients

Heart Disease Prediction¶

Cleveland Clinic Foundation recorded information on various patient characteristics, including age and chest pain. We will use it to classify the presence of heart disease in an individual.

Data dictionary:

Column Description
age age in years
sex sex (1 = male; 0 = female)
cp chest pain type
-- Value 1: typical angina
-- Value 2: atypical angina
-- Value 3: non-anginal pain
-- Value 4: asymptomatic
trestbps resting blood pressure (in mm Hg on admission to the hospital)
chol serum cholestoral in mg/dl
fbs (fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl) (1 = true; 0 = false)
restecg resting electrocardiographic results
-- Value 0: normal
-- Value 1: having ST-T wave abnormality (T wave inversions and/or ST elevation or depression of > 0.05 mV)
-- Value 2: showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estes' criteria
thalach maximum heart rate achieved
exang exercise induced angina (1 = yes; 0 = no)
oldpeak ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest
slope the slope of the peak exercise ST segment
-- Value 1: upsloping
-- Value 2: flat
-- Value 3: downsloping
ca number of major vessels (0-3) colored by flourosopy
thal 3 = normal; 6 = fixed defect; 7 = reversable defect
present diagnosis of heart disease (angiographic disease status)
-- Value 0: < 50% diameter narrowing
-- Value 1: > 50% diameter narrowing

We have 4 missing values in 'ca' and 2 missing values in 'thal'.

For 'ca':
With only 4 missing values out of 303 (about 1.3%), the best approach is to use simple imputation.
Since ca is an ordinal feature (0–3 vessels), we will impute missing values with the median of the column specific to the group of patients who have the same heart disease status. The median is preferred over the mean because ca is discrete and skewed.

For 'thal':
With only 2 missing values out of 303 (less than 1%) for the thal feature, the best approach is mode imputation — replace the missing values with the most frequent category.
Since thal is a categorical variable (3 = normal, 6 = fixed defect, 7 = reversible defect), using the mode preserves the distribution and avoids introducing bias.

In [9]:
# Replace ?s with NaN temporarily, then impute with median by heart disease status
df['ca'] = df['ca'].replace('?', np.nan)
df['ca'] = df['ca'].astype(float)
df['ca'] = df.groupby('present')['ca'].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))

# Replace ?s with NaN temporarily, then impute with mode by heart disease status
df['thal'] = df['thal'].replace('?', np.nan)
df['thal'] = df['thal'].astype(float)
df['thal'] = df.groupby('present')['thal'].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mode()[0] if not x.mode().empty else x.median()))   

#We check if the mode is not empty because Series.mode() returns an empty Series when all values in the group are unique or
# all are missing. Accessing .mode()[0] on an empty result would raise an IndexError.

The ca (number of major vessels colored by fluoroscopy) feature should be treated as an ordinal variable.

Although it represents counts (0–3), it reflects increasing severity of coronary artery disease:

  • 0: No vessels affected → lowest risk
  • 1–3: Increasing number of affected vessels → higher disease severity

Studies confirm it has a strong ordinal relationship with heart disease severity, where each additional vessel significantly increases the likelihood of disease. It is commonly used as a numerical or ordinal feature in models, with higher values indicating worse prognosis.

Target Distribution¶

Categorical columns proportions¶

In [14]:
data_cleaning.plot_categorical_bars(df,categorical_cols,rows=3)

We have 68% Males and 32% Females in the dataset. This imbalance in the dataset can cause problems when building a predictive model. Machine learning models trained on such imbalanced data may become biased toward the majority group (males), leading to reduced accuracy and fairness in predicting heart disease for females. Models can have higher performance on male patients due to overrepresentation, while female-specific patterns may be underlearned, resulting in disparities in prediction outcomes.

To mitigate this we will assess model performance separately for males and females to ensure equitable predictions. We will also use this column to straify the test train split.

Modeling¶

We will use Logistic Regression model. We will use f1_score as the scoring metric because it balances precision and recall. In medical diagnosis, the goal is to maximize the True Positive Rate and minimize the False Negative Rate. This means we need to have high recall.

Back to the top

pipe = Pipeline([
#    ('poly',PolynomialFeatures(interaction_only=True)),
    ('scaler',StandardScaler()),
    ('clf', LogisticRegression())

This approach reveals disparities in model performance across genders, helping ensure equitable predictions.

In [44]:
male_mask = (X_test['sex'] == 1)
female_mask = (X_test['sex'] == 0)

# Performance for males
acc_m = accuracy_score(y_test[male_mask], y_pred[male_mask])
prec_m = precision_score(y_test[male_mask], y_pred[male_mask])
rec_m = recall_score(y_test[male_mask], y_pred[male_mask])
f1_m = f1_score(y_test[male_mask], y_pred[male_mask])

# Performance for females
acc_f = accuracy_score(y_test[female_mask], y_pred[female_mask])
prec_f = precision_score(y_test[female_mask], y_pred[female_mask])
rec_f = recall_score(y_test[female_mask], y_pred[female_mask])
f1_f = f1_score(y_test[female_mask], y_pred[female_mask])

# Compare metrics to assess equity
print(f"Males:  Acc={acc_m:.3f}, Prec={prec_m:.3f}, Rec={rec_m:.3f}, F1={f1_m:.3f}")
print(f"Females: Acc={acc_f:.3f}, Prec={prec_f:.3f}, Rec={rec_f:.3f}, F1={f1_f:.3f}")  

Males:  Acc=0.881, Prec=0.909, Rec=0.870, F1=0.889

interpretation of logistic regression coefficients as odds ratios (OR = exp(coefficient)):¶

Feature Odds Ratio Interpretation
age OR = exp(-0.0565) = 0.945 Each additional year is associated with 5.5% lower odds of heart disease (unexpected, may need clinical review).
sex OR = exp(0.6076) = 1.836 Males have 83.6% higher odds of heart disease than females.
trestbps OR = exp(0.3532) = 1.424 Each 1 mm Hg increase in resting blood pressure → 42.4% higher odds.

Summary¶

Top positive predictors: sex, ca, cp_4, thal_7.0, exang, oldpeak.
Negative associations: age - clinically unexpected; consider checking data or model assumptions.

Feature Importance (using permutation)¶

On Training Set¶
In [46]:
result, ax = ds_modeling.plot_permutation_importance(grid_search.best_estimator_,X_train,y_train,scoring_metric='f1')

Note: Permutation importance does not reflect the intrinsic predictive value of a feature by itself but how important this feature is for a particular model.
On Test Set¶
In [47]:
result, ax = ds_modeling.plot_permutation_importance(grid_search.best_estimator_,X_test,y_test,scoring_metric='f1')

Note: Permutation importance does not reflect the intrinsic predictive value of a feature by itself but how important this feature is for a particular model.

Feature importance between the training and test set is not consistent- example for slope_2, exang etc. If a feature is important in the training set but not in the test set, the model may have learned noise or spurious patterns from that feature, leading to poor generalization. This overfitting can distort coefficient estimates — for example, causing a negative coefficient for age even if age is clinically expected to increase heart disease risk.

Conclusion¶

We have a fitted Logistic Regression model to the test data and

  • achieved 0.9 f1_score overall.
  • Even with the imbalance in 'sex' feature, model has equitable performance across genders.
  • The strongest predictors in the model are ca, cp, thal, exang and oldpeak.
  • males have 83% higher odds of having the heart disease compared to females.

We got negative association with age even though age is clinically expected to increase heart disease risk, likely due to overfitting in the model. This is something that can be improved by further increasing the regularization or by re-evluating the featues with inconsistent importance and transforming them.
